Each eDai contract has a specific maturity time. One eDai is worth one Chai at or after maturity time. At maturity, the eDai can be triggered to mature, which records the current rate and chi from MakerDAO and enables redemption. Redeeming an eDai means burning it, and the contract will retrieve Dai from Treasury equal to one Dai times the growth in chi since maturity. eDai also tracks the MakerDAO stability fee accumulator at the time of maturity, and the growth since. This is not used internally. Minting and burning of eDai is restricted to orchestrated contracts. @dev eDai is an eToken targeting Chai.
 Each eDai contract has a specific maturity time. One eDai is worth one Chai at or after maturity time.
 At maturity, the eDai can be triggered to mature, which records the current rate and chi from MakerDAO and enables redemption.
 Redeeming an eDai means burning it, and the contract will retrieve Dai from Treasury equal to one Dai times the growth in chi since maturity.
 eDai also tracks the MakerDAO stability fee accumulator at the time of maturity, and the growth since. This is not used internally.
 Minting and burning of eDai is restricted to orchestrated contracts. Redeeming and flash-minting is allowed to anyone.

@dev The constructor:
 Sets the name and symbol for the eDai token.
 Connects to Vat, Jug, Pot and Treasury.
 Sets the maturity date for the eDai, in unix time.
 Initializes chi and rate at maturity time as 1.0 with 27 decimals.

@dev Chi differential between maturity and now in RAY. Returns 1.0 if not mature.
 If rateGrowth < chiGrowth, returns rate.

@dev Rate differential between maturity and now in RAY. Returns 1.0 if not mature.
 rateGrowth is floored to 1.0.
@dev Mature eDai and capture chi and rate

devdoc.details: eDai is an eToken targeting Chai. Each eDai contract has a specific maturity time. One eDai is worth one Chai at or after maturity time. At maturity, the eDai can be triggered to mature, which records the current rate and chi from MakerDAO and enables redemption. Redeeming an eDai means burning it, and the contract will retrieve Dai from Treasury equal to one Dai times the growth in chi since maturity. eDai also tracks the MakerDAO stability fee accumulator at the time of maturity, and the growth since. This is not used internally. Minting and burning of eDai is restricted to orchestrated contracts. Redeeming and flash-minting is allowed to anyone.

addDelegate(address).details: Enable a delegate to act on the behalf of caller

addDelegateBySignature(address,address,u.details: Add a delegate through an encoded signature

approve(address,uint256).details: See {IERC20-approve}. Requirements: - `spender` cannot be the zero address.

batchOrchestrate(address,bytes4[]).details: Adds orchestration for the provided function signatures

burn(address,uint256).details: Burn eDai. Only callable by Controller contracts. This function can only be called by other Yield contracts, not users directly.

params.from: Wallet to burn the eDai from.

chiGrowth().details: Chi differential between maturity and now in RAY. Returns 1.0 if not mature. If rateGrowth < chiGrowth, returns rate.

constructor.details: The constructor: Sets the name and symbol for the eDai token. Connects to Vat, Jug, Pot and Treasury. Sets the maturity date for the eDai, in unix time. Initializes chi and rate at maturity time as 1.0 with 27 decimals.

decimals().details: Returns the number of decimals used to get its user representation. For example, if `decimals` equals `2`, a balance of `505` tokens should be displayed to a user as `5,05` (`505 / 10 ** 2`). Tokens usually opt for a value of 18, imitating the relationship between Ether and Wei. This is the value {ERC20} uses, unless {_setupDecimals} is called. NOTE: This information is only used for _display_ purposes: it in no way affects any of the arithmetic of the contract, including {IERC20-balanceOf} and {IERC20-transfer}.

decreaseAllowance(address,uint256).details: Atomically decreases the allowance granted to `spender` by the caller. This is an alternative to {approve} that can be used as a mitigation for problems described in {IERC20-approve}. Emits an {Approval} event indicating the updated allowance. Requirements: - `spender` cannot be the zero address. - `spender` must have allowance for the caller of at least `subtractedValue`.

params.data: User-defined data to pass on to `executeOnFlashMint()`
params.to: Wallet to mint the eDai in.

increaseAllowance(address,uint256).details: Atomically increases the allowance granted to `spender` by the caller. This is an alternative to {approve} that can be used as a mitigation for problems described in {IERC20-approve}. Emits an {Approval} event indicating the updated allowance. Requirements: - `spender` cannot be the zero address.

mature().details: Mature eDai and capture chi and rate

mint(address,uint256).details: Mint eDai. Only callable by Controller contracts. This function can only be called by other Yield contracts, not users directly.

params.to: Wallet to mint the eDai in.

name().details: Returns the name of the token.

params.signature: bytes4 signature of the function we are giving orchestrated access to. It seems to me a bad idea to give access to humans, and would use this only for predictable smart contracts.
params.user: Address of user or contract having access to this contract.

owner().details: Returns the address of the current owner.

permit(address,address,uint256,uint256,u.details: See {IERC2612-permit}. In cases where the free option is not a concern, deadline can simply be set to uint(-1), so it should be seen as an optional parameter

rateGrowth().details: Rate differential between maturity and now in RAY. Returns 1.0 if not mature. rateGrowth is floored to 1.0.

redeem(address,address,uint256).details: Burn eTokens and return their dai equivalent value, pulled from the Treasury During unwind, `treasury.pullDai()` will revert which is right. `from` needs to tell eDai to approve the burning of the eDai tokens. `from` can delegate to other addresses to redeem his eDai and put the Dai proceeds in the `to` wallet. The collateral needed changes according to series maturity and MakerDAO rate and chi, depending on collateral type.

params.to: Wallet to put the Dai in.

renounceOwnership().details: Leaves the contract without owner. It will not be possible to call `onlyOwner` functions anymore. Can only be called by the current owner. NOTE: Renouncing ownership will leave the contract without an owner, thereby removing any functionality that is only available to the owner.

revokeDelegate(address).details: Stop a delegate from acting on the behalf of caller

symbol().details: Returns the symbol of the token, usually a shorter version of the name.

transfer(address,uint256).details: See {IERC20-transfer}. Requirements: - `recipient` cannot be the zero address. - the caller must have a balance of at least `amount`.

transferFrom(address,address,uint256).details: See {IERC20-transferFrom}. Emits an {Approval} event indicating the updated allowance. This is not required by the EIP. See the note at the beginning of {ERC20}; Requirements: - `sender` and `recipient` cannot be the zero address. - `sender` must have a balance of at least `amount`. - the caller must have allowance for ``sender``'s tokens of at least `amount`.

transferOwnership(address).details: Transfers ownership of the contract to a new account (`newOwner`). Can only be called by the current owner.
